text: I'VE BEEN SO EXCITED FOR THIS MOVIE AND I WASN'T EXPECTING THEM TO ALREADY HAVE A TRAILER AND HOLY HECK THE ANIMATION AND ART STYLE IS SOOOOOOO SO SO BEAUTIFUL.   I really, really love the movement here. It has a sort of "flipbook animation" feel, or the feeling of going between two panels while you read a comic. It's really obvious at 0:24-0:27, as well as at 0:49-0:51. I LOVE IT. And I love the "drawn on" effect they gave Miles' facial features too. You can see this at 0:55. Also now that I paused it there I'm just noticing the beautiful screentoned effect of the white lighting shining on Miles' face from the left, as well as the digital paintbrush texture of his suit where the color changes from blue to red. They're really playing up the fact that Spiderman is a comic-book character, and I think that's a great choice. If they decided to make the animation look too real after three Spiderman reboots, it wouldn't bring anything new to the table.  I'm also suchhhh a fan of 0:14-0:17. The movement of the clothing especially. I love how the right side of his silhouette is smooth and static and the left side is flowing.   AND THAT SHOT WHERE HE'S FALLING AND THEY HAVE THE CAMERA UPSIDE DOWN. 0:34. THAT'S SO CREATIVE AND CAPTIVATING. THE COLORS ARE SO SO SO BEAUTIFUL IN THIS. I already know it's going to be my favorite movie of the year. Holy heck. The detail of the city, especially everything between 0:10-0:14, feels like an actual city. Too often in animation, cities have a sort of clean, candy feeling to them, and I've yet to see an animated city so beautifully urban, so wonderfully NEW YORK as it is here.  And 1:07. WHEW GOLLY DANG. THAT IS A BEAUTIFUL, BEAUTIFUL BEAUTIFUL SHOT. Edit: Also, I'm loving the "blur" effect. It's not truly a "blur" but like the effect when printer colors are misaligned.

text: I'm so excited for the expansion of the Spider Verse! I kinda got a taste of what it be like with the  ultimate Spiderma cartoon (I'm young so I haven't seen the 90's spider verse that people are talking about) and with the game I saw a bit more into it. So I'm ready for the cinematic stuff! And it looks like 616 Spidey comes in towards the end of the trailer, which has me really hyped up! Miles is a favorite of mine, right after Spider Gwen, so this will be fun to see on the big screen. And while I'm not an animation connoisseur, I think the animation looks good, (at least the arachnid kid looked really cool jumping off the side of the building) so I'm satisfied. Christmas 2018 is so far away! Gah! Torture!   Can't wait though! Please do good Sony, marvel needs an animation win.

I would have preferred a Static Shock animated movie. I like Miles, but he isn't the most original African descent character. Miles is a very deep & flushed out Black character. I just feel like the whole, Spider man number 2 thing is holding him back. Peter Parker will always be the original Spider man, Miles being one of many Spidermans & having Perter Parker as a mentor, makes Miles feel like a fan-character, a REALLY AWESOME fan character, but not as original or iconic as he could be. Miles doesn't have his own powers or suite, he seems like a unique character in another White comic book character's shadow.    If Disney does buy the Xmen from Fox, Fox is looking to sell, I'm hoping we get an BlackPanther meets Storm meets Miles event. In the Static Shock cartoon, Static meets Anansi, an Orisha God.    The animation styles reminds me of Disney XD's Tron: Uprising. I loved that cartoon, sucked it got cancelled. Also I don't trust Sony.

text: For everyone aaking why this isn't live action or in the MCU, I present 2 probable answers.   1.) Money. That shit's expensive yo.   2.) They just don't wanna. Spider-verse is a big story, and one that, with everything about to happen in the MCU, would make the MCU feel far more chaotic than they want it to. In this animated, non-canon format, they experiment a little and di what they want without having to worry about screwing up "the continuity."   Personally, I like it. This trailer presented to me a direction I honestly didn't see coming, and I kind of like it. Now please Sony, don't cannibalize it. Give us a comic book movie. The art is clearly gorgeous, now give the same thought and effort into the writing and give us a good animated comic book movie.

Everything else tho, looks great.

text: The animation is absolutely beautiful. This is the Spider-Man movie I've wanted to see for a long time: the lightness in Spider-Man's swings, the colourful lights of New York's skyline contrasting with the darkness of the night, it's all so breathtaking.  Sony is hitting all the right spots with the Spider-Man franchise lately; a deal with Marvel to let them use Peter Parker in the MCU, the upcoming Insomniac game, and now a Miles Morales movie. I hope the movie ends up being as impressive as the trailer suggests.

text: It looks really gorgeous (the loss of frames in the animation notwithstanding) and I think I really dig the idea of an animated Spiderman, and even it being a new character.  However, I just can't swallow the *NAME* being "spiderman."  Just... I mean, call him something else. Think of another name. It's like working with a guy who's name is Matt and like 5 other guys (and 1 woman) are *ALSO* named Matt.  We already have problems with Ghostbusters. Which one do you mean when you say Ghostbusters? I dunno, I guess I'll put the year after it in parenthesis so we can tell them apart :P  Or... *OR* you could give a new character a new name and have them stand on their own merit. Because the character looks cool. He shouldn't have to steal or even borrow some other character's name to be successful.

text: My one fear with this is that Sony is going to repeat their past mistakes by focusing on world building over the actual substance of the script, as they did with the other movies. This is alluded through the title "Into the Spider-Verse" and one of title cards that played during the trailer "Enter the Universe." This is an entirely new Spider-Man to audiences. Isn't it more important to focus with the character first, rather than explore the depths of the Spidey-Verse, which is arguably one of Spider-Man's best story line concepts, requiring the character to already be established to really get the irony that is created through the contrasts between the Spider-Men. Still, the animation does look great, and there is quite a bit of visual story telling with the character design of Miles, so this could still work. I'm just not sure if Sony knows how to make it work.

Why not just make it so Miles became Spider-Man after Peter died... and then sometime down the line just as he's getting used to be being spider-man, bam! peter is alive again and ready to be spider-man, giving Miles a bit of an identity crisis. text: This film could end up being one of the best superhero films of the last couple decades. I'm totally serious. So from this trailer, we've already seen some STUNNING cinematography and staging. The writing team is chock full of great writers (my favourite being Alex Hirsch, creator of Gravity Falls) who have proven themselves with some incredible projects. And the animation is such a breath of fresh air and great in its own right. The smears look great, the colour palette is wonderfully neon, and there are some really great details thrown in (for example, if you slow the trailer down, you can get a quick glimpse of the spider sense as Miles almost hits the roof of the building before swinging away). All in all: very excited.

text: Okay I'm gonna help out a majority of this comment section XD when Miles is standing at the tombstone that is Peter Parker's grave. Now here's the thing, and stay with me because you might get confused. The Peter Parker in that grave isn't the main true Peter. That's ultimate Spider-Man. Let me explain, back in the later 2000s Marvel decided to make a comic line separate from their main 616 World. It was dubbed the ultimate universe. The purpose was to revamp and update Marvel characters to a more modern time. So in the ultimate universe, Peter Parker dies. Then later Miles Morales takes up the role of the new ultimate Spider-Man in the ultimate universe. In the spiderverse comic story main Peter Parker does get involved with Miles so we'll probably see the og friendly neighborhood spiderman.

Smurfs: The Lost Village is passable, but The Star is only tolerable. Judging by the sole trailer for this film, Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse may or may not save Sony Pictures Animation incredibly, but this trailer for Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse is too badass for words, so Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse could be one of the only great Sony Pictures Animation films besides Surf's Up and the Aardman movies.

text: To all those thinking this is apart of the MCU. IT ISN'T!!! If any of you bothered to read the comics, which majority of you in the comments obviously haven't. There are multiple universes in the comics, thus multiple Earths. Now on Earth 616, in which all major storylines and cannons take place. And also which the MCU is mainly based off. Peter Parker is Spider-Man, whereas in Miles Morales' universe (Ultimate Universe) Peter is sadly killed off... And a lot of fans were super pissed. So in Miles' universe he is Spidey. Whereas in the official universe Peter Parker is still your "Friendly Neighborhood Wallcrawler". Other examples of Peter Parker not being Spider-Man. Are Spider-Gwen in which, Peter is dead. And Gwen Stacy if you remember Peter's dead girlfriend. Is her universe's Spider-Man. Whereas in 616 she's unfortunately dead, after Peter snaps her neck trying to save her... Next Spider-Girl, in her universe Peter and Mary-Jane are married. And have a daughter May " Mayday" Parker. Peter is forced to retire as Spider-Man. After receiving crippling injuries from a battle with Hobgoblin I believe. And his daughter takes up the mantle. Hope this helps anyone confused...

text: Hmm. The animation actually is a huge letdown. choppy framerate, cheesy overused CGI stylings, and mundane average directed shots that have been on a  repeated loop through modern animated feature films as of the last 10 years. Was hoping for traditional animation at best, with real heart. not this cold machine produced mess. sorry folks but is this is eye candy ill avoid the cavity. I'm speaking strictly of animation here as an animator myself, storyboard director and comic artist. Good work to those who worked hard on it but the final product leaves a lot to be desired. trying too hard guys...no suspense or feeling of real agility here... The story could be great which is what we are after, but again, this animation just leaves a sour taste in my mouth. Will watch, but defintly do not agree that the animation is anything wonderful. Progression and higher budgets seem to just produce more average or cold results in the field these days... Summed up, your movie looks like a Disney original daytime series.

text: Let us forget possible agendas. Let us forget what age we live in for a second. The age of "information." Really I think we often miss the point of what power and responsibility truly mean... We ALL have an opportunity TODAY to be better. To actually make the world a better place. Sure you won't have super powers doing it, but you have power inside of you... You have power around you. The power of human connection. The power of choice. The power to believe and to do. Intentions aren't enough... you have to mean it by doing and leading by example. "The idea was to be a symbol. Batman, could be anybody. That was the point." "You know Zorro... could be anybody." These things mean something to me. I will live my life knowing that I am not held back by what others think and will NEVER stop someone from doing something that they believe in or think is right. Should there be a black Spider-Man? The answer is simple. What does it matter? As long as the individual is helping people because they have been given the gifts, or resources, or knowledge, or strength OR WHATEVER it might be. That is what matters. That is the point. This is like... the first time I have ever written a YouTube comment. I'm not on the internet constantly fighting losing battles with trolls. Honestly, I will probably bring some of them out of the woodwork. I'm just tired... I am tired of seeing people divided, and I will remain tired, because people will always be people. People aren't perfect. Life is hard. Batman never could win the War, neither could Spider-Man or any of our heroes. But they did it anyway. To the people who genuinely care about superheroes and about comics and the movies and games and childhood memories, and the God damned lessons they taught all of us. I say this. a Hero comes in many shapes and sizes, and in this day and age. I believe all of us. All of us different shaped and sized, and colored, and spoken people. Have heroes inside of us. Otherwise who could put up with this bullshit? So go out there. Do some good, make our heroes... who exist only in our own hearts... proud. YouTube fighting about race or corporation agendas, or politics or which movie sucks and doesn't suck and how "They ruined Spider-Man." is the last place Peter Parker would want you to be.
author: Marcelo Sepulveda

text: Was working at a movie theatre when this came out. A comic loving colleague told me there was another Spider-man film coming, I couldn't have cared less. Then the two of us were waiting for a film to start one day, this was the last trailer before the lights dimmed. I have never been that shocked at how quickly I became hyped for a film, mouth hanging open and a tear just chillin in my eye. My Colleague on the other hand yelled "MILES!!" on top of her lungs, the people in the theatre thought she was insane.
